{
  "text_segment": "Let us return to the “Examination.” A young lady read an essay “Is this, then, Life?” A favorite theme. She appeared on the stage and delivered a highly wrought composition. She presented a picture of a youthful, wayward soul, yearning for the festive scenes; in a word, “the world.” She sought it—found it—and had got drunk on its intoxicating draughts. The first sip of pleasure, on being exalted to the head of the social life in the village, had been delirious; the succeeding draughts had been less grateful; the latest one had cooled forever the fires that burned in her heart and now, the chill disillusionment weighing upon her, she cast down the goblet of life and longed for the grave. A thunderous discharge of applause followed. The boy-orators were apparently Zadkiels and Nostradamuses in their thoughts and words. The villagers were amazed and delighted. A slim, melancholy girl, whose face had the “interesting” pallor of wasting ill health, delivered a composition in a thin, frightened voice. Its title was “A Missouri Maiden’s Farewell to Alabama.” The theme was the parting of a maiden from her native land—Alabama—and her friends. Its conclusion was a touching reference to the lilies and the birds of Alabama. It was received with a great deal of favor. Then followed the grand event of the evening. A dark-complexioned young lady, with a tragic face, read in a measured, solemn voice a composition which she had written, and which was the pride of the school. Its title was “A Vision.” It was a tale of a storm-tossed soul on a stormy sea. The soul was saved at last by a life-boat labeled “Religion.” The girl had been wasting her oil. She had written this composition, which was about ten pages of manuscript, in the intimate seclusion of her own room, and had read it to no one. It was a triumph. The prize, a copy of “Pope’s Essay on Man,” was awarded to her. The mayor of the village, in delivering the prize, made a speech. He said that it was a poem. He said it was without fault. He said that he had read a great many poems in his time, but that this one was the most beautiful. He was sure that Daniel Webster himself could not have written such a poem. The elocution of the young lady had been fine—he had been affected to tears by it. The villagers were proud of her. The school-teacher was proud of her. The parents were proud of her. She was the heroine of the night."
}
